    "location": "Section 4 Module Structure",
    "description": "The Reference aggregate has UI space under app/(dashboard)/reference but no domain/application home under lib/. Compound, Profile, Citation, catalog search, soft-delete behavior, and profile publication invariants are therefore not assigned to an implementation boundary.",
    "suggestion": "Add lib/reference/ with catalog services, profile queries, publication/archival logic, and seed/import responsibilities."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P1",
    "category": "coverage",
    "location": "Sections 2.1 and 4 Tracker",
    "description": "Tracker architecture covers dose logging and protocols but omits subjective outcome logging, outcome-dose correlation, cycle analytics, protocol clone/restart, pause/resume, and batch logging as explicit architectural responsibilities.",
    "suggestion": "Expand Tracker into submodules for protocols, cycles, dose logs, batch logging, injection-site rotation, outcome logs, and timeline projections."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P1",
    "category": "coverage",
    "location": "Sections 2.1 and 4 Auth",
    "description": "Auth is described only as registration, login, and session management, but the PRD/domain model require managed-user invitations, password reset tokens, onboarding state, account deletion requests, and data export requests.",
    "suggestion": "Add Auth/Admin/Data Privacy responsibilities explicitly: invites, reset tokens, onboarding state, account deletion workflow, export request workflow, Resend email delivery, and R2 export storage."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P1",
    "category": "coverage",
    "location": "Sections 2.1, 3.2, and 4 Ordering",
    "description": "Ordering architecture mentions vendor catalog and Telegram send, but does not assign homes for Vendor, vendor products, order line items, payment confirmation, stale detection, send_method, manual fallback advancement, or receipt-to-inventory updates.",
    "suggestion": "Define lib/ordering submodules for vendors, catalog products, cart/order composition, MTProto dispatch, payment confirmation, status state machine, stale-order job, and received-order inventory handoff."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P0",
    "category": "correctness",
    "location": "Section 3.2 Flow: Place Telegram Order",
    "description": "The order data flow stops at Sent and omits the PRD hard-gate payment flow: vendor confirmation capture, wallet address and amount display, acknowledgement, PaymentSent transition, optional tx ID, Received transition, and inventory creation. This fails the 100% crypto payment safety requirement.",
    "suggestion": "Extend the flow to cover Draft -> Sent -> Confirmed -> PaymentSent -> Received, including blocked PaymentSent without PaymentConfirmation, audit events for every transition, and inventory update prompts on receipt."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P1",
    "category": "correctness",
    "location": "Section 3.1 Flow: Log a Dose",
    "description": "The dose logging flow unconditionally decrements Vial.remainingMg. PRD behavior allows logging without an active vial, supports skipped doses, permits actual dose edits, and requires warnings rather than hard failure when inventory is zero.",
    "suggestion": "Split dose logging into validated cases: Logged with vial decrement, Logged without vial warning, Skipped with no decrement, batch log transaction, and same-day edit rules. Include audit writes in the same transaction."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P1",
    "category": "consistency",
    "location": "Section 4 Module Structure vs ADR-015",
    "description": "ADR-015 requires ordering flows under /ordering, ordering actions under app/actions/ordering, RBAC capability checks, and DISABLE_ORDERING enforcement. The architecture places ordering under app/(dashboard)/ordering, uses a generic app/actions directory, and does not mention the feature flag or route blocking.",
    "suggestion": "Update the module structure and guard model to include app/(dashboard)/ordering or app/ordering as the only ordering route root, app/actions/ordering, lib/ordering, RBAC capability checks, and DISABLE_ORDERING checks at UI, action, and route-handler boundaries."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P1",
    "category": "consistency",
    "location": "Sections 6, 7, and 8 vs ADR-012",
    "description": "Railway Cron is required for dose reminders, stale-order detection, and audit purges, but the architecture only says api contains cron endpoints. It does not define scheduled job modules, secured cron routes, CRON_SECRET validation, or job ownership.",
    "suggestion": "Add app/api/cron/* secured by CRON_SECRET and lib/jobs/* implementations for reminder dispatch, stale order marking, audit purge, export processing, deletion execution, and backup/health checks where applicable."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P1",
    "category": "coverage",
    "location": "Sections 2.1, 6, and 7 Reminders",
    "description": "Dose reminders are a PRD Should Have and ADR-012 cron driver, but they appear only as an extension point. The architecture does not cover Web Push subscriptions, notification permission state, Resend fallback email, or reminder-time storage.",
    "suggestion": "Add a Reminders component with push subscription persistence, reminder preferences, Railway Cron dispatch, Web Push delivery, Resend fallback, and failure logging."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P2",
    "category": "correctness",
    "location": "Section 3.1 Offline-First Sync",
    "description": "Offline sync is underspecified for multi-user auth, browser-local date resolution, replay ordering, same-day edit cutoffs, duplicate confirmation, batch logs, and conflict handling across devices. A single idempotency key rule is not enough to make the flow feasible.",
    "suggestion": "Define the IndexedDB event schema, sync API contract, authenticated user scoping, scheduledDate timezone derivation, idempotency strategy, replay ordering, conflict responses, and client reconciliation behavior."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P2",
    "category": "consistency",
    "location": "Section 2.2 MTProto Integration Layer",
    "description": "The singleton persistent MTProto client conflicts with the PRD scalability requirement that the API be stateless and horizontally viable. Railway always-on hosting supports MTProto, but a process singleton can break across restarts, rolling deploys, or future multi-instance scaling.",
    "suggestion": "Make encrypted session strings the durable source of truth and define a reconnectable per-user client/session manager with lifecycle cleanup, restart recovery, and a documented single-instance v1 constraint if horizontal scaling is deferred."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P2",
    "category": "consistency",
    "location": "Sections 7 and 8 vs ADR-013",
    "description": "Observability is reduced to Sentry and Railway metrics, but PRD/ADR requirements include P0 alerting within 15 minutes, Telegram send failure visibility, uptime monitoring, backup verification alerts, and audit write failure alerting.",
    "suggestion": "Add an observability architecture covering Sentry alert rules, external uptime checks, backup verification events, audit-write failure handling, and user-visible failure states for ordering, dose, vial, and export flows."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P2",
    "category": "readiness",
    "location": "Section 4 Module Structure",
    "description": "The module structure is too coarse for parallel agent implementation. app/actions is global, lib modules mix domain and infrastructure, and cross-domain flows such as order receipt -> vial creation and dose log -> inventory decrement have no explicit ownership boundary.",
    "suggestion": "Restructure each bounded context into clear slices such as domain, application/actions, infrastructure/repositories, and UI/routes. Add explicit integration services or application use cases for cross-domain workflows."
  },
  {
    "severity": "P2",
    "category": "readiness",
    "location": "Missing Testing Architecture vs ADR-008",
    "description": "The architecture does not include a testing structure despite ADR-008 requiring Vitest and Playwright, with 100% coverage for reconstitution math and payment safety flows plus E2E coverage for offline sync.",
    "suggestion": "Add test ownership to the architecture: unit tests for reconstitution and domain invariants, integration tests for audit/transactions/idempotency, and Playwright E2E suites for payment confirmation, offline sync, managed-user access, and ordering fallback."
  }
]
